<section xml:id="sec-linear-harder" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>First-Order Linear ODEs: A Harder Example</title>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       INTRO PROSE
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <!-- PROSE: motivating intro -->
<p>
  Now for some practice solving a first-order linear ODE. This will help reinforce all the ideas we just went through, plus
  we will be getting our hands a little messier!
</p>
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       ACTIVITY
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <activity xml:id="act-linear-harder">
    <title>Practice: Solve <m>(x^4+5)y' + x^3 y = x^3</m></title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
       In this activity we work through solving a first-order line ODE that is slightly more involved than the previous examples
        The first few parts will reinforce steps we already discussed, so this will be a great way to practice these steps. The only big difference is that in the last step, where the final integral is a little messier.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <!-- TASK 1: identify P(x) and Q(x) -->
<task xml:id="task-harder-pq">
      <title>Identifying <m>P(x)</m> and <m>Q(x)</m></title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the ODE
          <me>(x^4+5)y' + x^3 y = x^3.</me>
          Which of the following correctly identifies <m>P(x)</m> and <m>Q(x)</m> when this equation is written in standard form?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p><m>P(x) = \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m> and <m>Q(x) = \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m></p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Correct! In standard form <m>y' + P(x)y = Q(x)</m>: <m>y' + \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}y = \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m>.
              Dividing both sides by <m>(x^4+5)</m> gives <m>P(x) = \frac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m> and <m>Q(x) = \frac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m>.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>P(x) = x^3</m> and <m>Q(x) = x^3</m></p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Not quite. In standard form <m>y' + P(x)y = Q(x)</m>: <m>y' + \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}y = \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m>.
              The coefficient on <m>y'</m> must be 1, so you need to divide every term by <m>(x^4+5)</m> first.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>P(x) = \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m> and <m>Q(x) = x^3</m></p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Close, but not quite. In standard form <m>y' + P(x)y = Q(x)</m>: <m>y' + \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}y = \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m>.
              <m>P(x)</m> is correct, but <m>Q(x)</m> needs to be divided by <m>(x^4+5)</m> too -- every term gets divided.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>P(x) = x^3</m> and <m>Q(x) = \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m></p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Close, but not quite. In standard form <m>y' + P(x)y = Q(x)</m>: <m>y' + \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}y = \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m>.
              <m>Q(x)</m> is correct, but <m>P(x)</m> also needs to be divided by <m>(x^4+5)</m>.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </task>

    <!-- TASK 2: find rho(x) unsimplified -->
    <task xml:id="task-harder-rho-unsimplified">
      <title>Finding the Integrating Factor</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Now that we have <m>P(x) = \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m>, find the integrating factor
          <m>\rho(x).</m>
          Stop after integrating (the next part will simplify <m>\rho</m> further).
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <ul>
          <li><p>Recall that <m>\rho(x) = e^{\int P(x)\,dx}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>To evaluate <m>\int \frac{x^3}{x^4+5}\,dx</m> use a u-sub (what should u be?)</p></li>
          <li><p>Don't simplify the resulting <m>\rho(x)</m> yet, that's the next part.</p></li>
        </ul>
      </hint>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We compute <m>\int P(x)\,dx = \int \frac{x^3}{x^4+5}\,dx</m> using a u-substitution with <m>u = x^4 + 5</m>.
        </p>
        <solution>
          <title>U-substitution details (read if stuck)</title>
          <p>
            Let <m>u = x^4 + 5</m>, so <m>du = 4x^3\,dx</m>, which means <m>x^3\,dx = \frac{1}{4}du</m>. Then:
            <md>
              <mrow>\int \frac{x^3}{x^4+5}\,dx \amp= \int \frac{1}{u} \cdot \frac{1}{4}\,du</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp= \frac{1}{4}\int \frac{1}{u}\,du</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp= \frac{1}{4}\ln|u| + C</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp= \frac{1}{4}\ln(x^4+5).</mrow>
            </md>
            (We drop the absolute value since <m>x^4 + 5 \gt 0</m> always, and drop <m>C</m> since we only need one antiderivative.)
          </p>
        </solution>
        <p>
          So,<m>\int P(x)\,dx= \frac{1}{4}\ln(x^4+5)</m>, meaning the integrating factor is
          <me>\rho(x) = e^{\frac{1}{4}\ln(x^4+5)}.</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>

    <!-- TASK 3: simplify rho(x) -->
    <task xml:id="task-harder-rho-simplified">
      <title>Simplifying the Integrating Factor</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          From the previous part, <m>\rho(x) = e^{\frac{1}{4}\ln(x^4+5)}</m>. Which of the following correctly simplifies this?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement><p><m>\rho(x) = (x^4+5)^{1/4}</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Correct! Using the log property <m>e^{a\ln(u)} = u^a</m>, we get
              <m>e^{\frac{1}{4}\ln(x^4+5)} = (x^4+5)^{1/4}</m>.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>\rho(x) = \frac{1}{4}(x^4+5)</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Not quite. The <m>\frac{1}{4}</m> is in the exponent of <m>e</m>, not a coefficient out front.
              Use the property <m>e^{a\ln(u)} = u^a</m> with <m>a = \frac{1}{4}</m>.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>\rho(x) = (x^4+5)^4</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Close in structure, but the exponent should be <m>\frac{1}{4}</m>, not <m>4</m>.
              We have <m>e^{\frac{1}{4}\ln(x^4+5)} = (x^4+5)^{1/4}</m>.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>\rho(x) = e^{x^4+5}</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Remember that <m>e^{\frac{1}{4}\ln(x^4+5)} \ne e^{x^4+5}</m>.
              Use the log property <m>e^{a\ln(u)} = u^a</m> to simplify.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </task>

    <!-- TASK 4: finish solving -->
    <task xml:id="task-harder-solve">
      <title>Finishing the Solution</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The next steps -- multiplying by <m>\rho(x)</m>, recognizing the product rule collapse, and integrating -- always work out the same way. 
          <alert>So we can always jump directly to:</alert>
          <me>\rho(x) \cdot y = \int \rho(x)\, Q(x)\,dx.</me>
          Fill in <m>\rho(x)</m> and <m>Q(x)</m> and finish solving for <m>y</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <ul>
          <li><p> Substitute <m>\rho(x) = (x^4+5)^{1/4}</m> and <m>Q(x) = \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m> into <m>\rho(x) \cdot y = \int \rho(x)\,Q(x)\,dx</m> to get your first line.</p></li>
          <li><p>Simplify the integrand -- notice that <m>(x^4+5)^{1/4} \cdot \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5} = x^3(x^4+5)^{-3/4}</m>. Then use the substitution <m>u = x^4+5</m>.</p></li>
        </ul>
      </hint>
       <solution>
        <p>
          Substituting in <m>\rho(x)</m> and <m>Q(x)</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>\rho(x) \cdot y \amp= \int \rho(x)\, Q(x)\,dx</mrow>
            <mrow>(x^4+5)^{1/4}\, y \amp= \int (x^4+5)^{1/4} \cdot \frac{x^3}{x^4+5}\,dx</mrow>
            <mrow>(x^4+5)^{1/4}\, y \amp= \int x^3(x^4+5)^{-3/4}\,dx.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <solution>
          <title>U-substitution details (read if stuck)</title>
          <p>
            Let <m>u = x^4+5</m>, so <m>du = 4x^3\,dx</m>, meaning <m>x^3\,dx = \frac{1}{4}du</m>. Then:
            <md>
              <mrow>\int x^3(x^4+5)^{-3/4}\,dx \amp= \frac{1}{4}\int u^{-3/4}\,du</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp= \frac{1}{4} \cdot \frac{u^{1/4}}{1/4} + C</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp= u^{1/4} + C</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp= (x^4+5)^{1/4} + C.</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
        <p>
          So we have:
          <md>
            <mrow>(x^4+5)^{1/4}\, y \amp= (x^4+5)^{1/4} + C</mrow>
            <mrow>y \amp= 1 + C(x^4+5)^{-1/4}.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>

   
  </activity>

      <p>
        Let's recap the steps for this problem:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><alert>Step 1.</alert> Divide through by <m>(x^4+5)</m> to get standard form, giving <m>P(x) = \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m> and <m>Q(x) = \dfrac{x^3}{x^4+5}</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Step 2.</alert> Find <m>\rho(x) = e^{\int P(x)\,dx}</m>. The integral required a u-substitution, giving <m>e^{\frac{1}{4}\ln(x^4+5)}</m>, which simplifies via log rules to <m>(x^4+5)^{1/4}</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Step 3.</alert> Jump directly to <m>\rho(x) \cdot y = \int \rho(x)\,Q(x)\,dx</m> and evaluate the right-hand side, which required another u-substitution.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Step 4.</alert> Divide both sides by <m>\rho(x)</m> to solve for <m>y</m>. Remember that <m>C</m> gets divided by <m>\rho(x)</m>, too! The final answer is <m>y=1+C(x^4+5)^{-1/4}</m>, <alert>not</alert> <m>y=1+C</m>.</p></li>
      </ul>
   
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       VIDEO
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
